[With the addition of Tajikistan (European region) and Comoros (African region) reported on 1 May 2020, the number of countries and territories reporting confirmed cases of COVID-19 is now 214. This includes 19 countries (including 4 territories) from the Western Pacific region, 61 countries (including 7 territories) from the European region, 10 countries from the Southeast Asia region, 22 countries (including 1 territory) from the Eastern Mediterranean region, 54 countries (including 19 territories) from the Americas region, and 48 countries (including 2 territories) from the African region.

In the 24 hours since the last WHO update:
----------------------------------------
The Americas region reported 48 674 new cases (52.9% of the global newly reported cases) and 3109 deaths (53.6% of the global newly reported deaths). Of the newly confirmed cases in the region, 65.3% were reported by the USA, followed by Brazil at 14.8%, Peru at 6.3%, and Canada at 3.3%. Recognizing the USA data are overshadowing the regional proportions, without including the reported newly confirmed cases from the USA, Brazil reported 42.7% of the newly reported cases in the region, followed by Peru at 18.0%, Canada at 9.5%, Mexico at 8.4%, Ecuador at 8.3%, Chile at 5.8%, and the Dominican Republic at 1.9%.

The European region reported 30 620 new cases (33.3% of the global newly reported cases) and 2386 deaths (41.1% of the global newly reported deaths). Russia reported 31.4% of the newly confirmed cases in the region, the UK 20.3%, Germany 8.4%, Turkey 7.1%, Italy 6.4%, and Belarus 2.9%.

The Eastern Mediterranean region reported 6406 new cases (7.0% of the global newly reported cases) and 143 deaths (2.5% of the global newly reported deaths). Saudi Arabia reported 21.0% of the regional newly reported cases, followed by Pakistan at 20.2%, Iran at 15.7%, Qatar 10.7%, and the United Arab Emirates at 8.7%.

The African region reported 1310 new cases (1.4% of the global newly reported cases) and 40 deaths (0.69% of the global newly reported deaths). South Africa reported 23.2% of the newly reported cases in the region in the past 24 hours, followed by Nigeria at 18.2%, Cameroon at 18.1%, Algeria at 11.3%, and Senegal at 6.9%.

The Western Pacific region reported 1565 new cases (1.7% of the global newly reported cases) and 39 deaths (0.67% of the global newly reported deaths). Singapore reported 59.6% of the newly reported cases, followed by the Philippines at 18.1%, Japan at 16.9%, and Malaysia at 4.4%.

The South-East Asia region reported 3402 new cases (3.7% of the global newly reported cases) and 82 deaths (1.4% of the global newly reported deaths). India reported 67.4% of newly reported cases, followed by Bangladesh at 16.8% and Indonesia at 12.7%. Removing India from the denominator, Bangladesh represents 51.5% of the newly reported cases, Indonesia represents 39.0%, and the Maldives 6.5%.

Figure 2. Epidemic curve of confirmed COVID-19 cases, by date of report and WHO region, 30 Dec 2019 through 2 May 2020, at the source URL above, is an excellent representation of the epidemic starting in the Western Pacific, transitioning to multiregional activity as the virus travelled. One sees the contribution of the ongoing epidemics in Europe and the increasing cases in the Americas region, fueled by the USA, but other countries are following suit. The curve tends to drop over the weekends and rebounds following the weekend.

A somewhat repetitive but necessary reminder: It is clear that the number of reported confirmed cases differs from different reporting websites and is somewhat a function of time of day the website is updated. For example, I note the time we've accessed the Johns Hopkin's CSSE or Worldometer website, but by the time the post is actually finished with the editing process, those numbers have, at times, significantly changed. Case counting is clearly a moving target, and depending upon when the website updates, the numbers may be different. I try to start each post with the latest figures for the calendar day (the John Hopkins CSSE or Worldometer table) and close with the figures from the start of the calendar day (the WHO tables), defining the calendar day as DST (now GMT-4). - Mod.UBA

